from9January1342to8January1343–1406","1344–Female":"1344–Deceased","1346–Female":"1346–Deceased","1368–1396":"1368–1396","1316–1383":"1316–1383","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","about 1406":"about 1406","1368":"1368","ABT 1340":"about 1340","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","2 August 1396":"2 August 1396","1342":"from 9 January 1342 to 8 January 1343","1320":"1320","1406":"1406","Wolcott, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Walcot, Shropshire, England":"Walcot, Shropshire, England","England":"England","(, Norfolk, England)":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wolcott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Surrey): habitational name from Wollacott in Thrushelton (Devon), named from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfnōth</i> + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain.","History: Henry Wolcott (1578–1655), clothier, came from Tolland, Somerset, England, and settled in Windsor, CT, in 1636. His grandson Roger (1679–1767) was colonial governor of CT; his great-grandson Oliver (1726–1797) was a signer of the Declaration of Independence."],"variants":[{"name":"Woolcott","meanings":["English: variant of   Wolcott  ."]},{"name":"Woolcock","meanings":["English (Cornwall): probably a variant of   Wolcott  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":39,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Wolcott was born from 9 January 1342 to 8 January 1343, in Walcot, Shropshire, England, his father, Sir John Walcott Knight, was 27 and his mother, Alice Clopton, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Maude Le Scrope. He died about 1406, in England."},"et":{"1342–about 1406":"9. jaanuar 1342 kuni 8. jaanuar 1343–umbes 1406","1342–1406":"9.jaanuar1342kuni8.jaanuar1343–1406","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1368–1396":"1368–1396","1316–1383":"1316–1383","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","about 1406":"umbes 1406","1368":"1368","ABT 1340":"umbes 1340","1346":"1346","1344":"1344","2 August 1396":"2. august 1396","1342":"9. jaanuar 1342 kuni 8. jaanuar 1343","1320":"1320","1406":"1406","Wolcott, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Walcott, Norfolk, England":"Walcott, Norfolk, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Walcot, Shropshire, England":"Walcot, Shropshire, England","England":"England","(, Norfolk, England)":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1342–about 1406":"vuodesta 9. tammikuuta 1342 vuoteen 8. tammikuuta 1343–noin 1406","1342–1406":"vuodesta9.tammikuuta1342vuoteen8.tammikuuta1343–1406","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1368–1396":"1368–1396","1316–1383":"1316–1383","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1396":"1396","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1316":"1316","about 1406":"noin 1406",